By: Zhuangzi
Locus:
  Chapter: 4
  Paragraph: 47
Title: In The World Of Men
---
When Confucius visited Ch'u, Chieh Yu, the madman of Ch'u, wandered by
his gate crying, "Phoenix, phoenix, how his virtue failed! The future
you cannot wait for; the past you cannot pursue. When the world has the
Way, the sage succeeds; when the world is without the Way, the sage
survives. In times like the present, we do well to escape penalty. Good
fortune is light as a feather, but nobody knows how to hold it up.
Misfortune is heavy as the earth, but nobody knows how to stay out of
its way. Leave off, leave off - this teaching men virtue! Dangerous,
dangerous - to mark off the ground and run! Fool, fool - don't spoil my
walking! I walk a crooked way - don't step on my feet. The mountain
trees do
